=> Singleton in Java is a design pattern that restricts the instantiation of a class to a single instance and provides a global point of access to that instance. This is useful when exactly one object is needed to coordinate actions across the system.

=> While creating singleton we have to ensure only one object is created and that object can be accessed globally. There are several ways to implement a singleton in Java, each with its own advantages and disadvantages. Here are six common ways to write a singleton in Java:      

=> Common things to consider when implementing a singleton:
    1. All constructor should be private to prevent direct instantiation.
    2. A private static or private static final variable to hold the single instance of the class.
       a. A private static variable is initialized when the class is loaded, and it can be lazily initialized when the instance is first requested.
       b. A private static final variable is initialized when the class is loaded and cannot be changed afterward, ensuring thread safety without synchronization.
    3. A static method to provide global access to the single instance.

=> 6 Ways to Write a Singleton in Java:
    -> Static Eager Singleton Class:
    
        -> Eager means the object is created early and kept ready to use.
        -> When a .java file is compiled, it generates a .class file.
        -> The JVM loads the .class file into memory when the class is needed.
        -> When the class is loaded, static variables are initialized.
        -> Since the singleton instance is declared as static, the object is created during class loading itself.
        -> Without static, the object will NOT be created during class loading.
        -> Static variables are initialized only once when the class is loaded.
        
        -> Example: Refer StaticEagerSingleton.java
        
        -> Flow:
            -> StaticEagerSingleton.java is compiled into StaticEagerSingleton.class
            -> JVM loads StaticEagerSingleton.class into memory
            -> The static variable 'instance' is initialized
            -> new StaticEagerSingleton() executes and creates the singleton object
            -> The getInstance() method returns the already created instance

        -> Advantages:
            -> Simple to implement
            -> Thread-safe without synchronization

        -> Disadvantages:
            -> Instance is created even if it is never used
            -> Can lead to unnecessary memory/resource usage
    
    -> Dynamic Lazy Singleton Class:
    
        -> Lazy means the object is created only when it is needed.

        -> The singleton instance is not created until the getInstance() method is called for the first time.

        -> This approach can save resources if the singleton object is not always required.
            
        -> Example: Refer DynamicLazySingleton.java
            
        -> Flow:
            -> DynamicLazySingleton.java is compiled into DynamicLazySingleton.class
            -> JVM loads DynamicLazySingleton.class into memory
            -> The static variable 'instance' is initialized to null
            -> When getInstance() is called for the first time, it checks whether 'instance' is null
            -> If null, it creates a new instance of DynamicLazySingleton and assigns it to 'instance'
            -> Subsequent calls to getInstance() return the already created instance

        -> Advantages:
            -> Instance is created only when needed
            -> Saves memory/resources

        -> Disadvantages:
            -> Not thread-safe without synchronization
            -> Multiple threads may create multiple instances simultaneously in a multithreaded environment


    -> Dynamic Lazy Improved Singleton Class:
        
        -> This approach is similar to Dynamic Lazy Singleton but adds synchronization to make it thread-safe.

        -> The getInstance() method is synchronized, ensuring that only one thread can execute it at a time.

        -> This prevents multiple threads from creating multiple singleton objects simultaneously.
            
        -> Example: Refer DynamicLazyImprovedSingleton.java
            
        -> Flow:
            -> DynamicLazyImprovedSingleton.java is compiled into DynamicLazyImprovedSingleton.class
            -> JVM loads DynamicLazyImprovedSingleton.class into memory
            -> The static variable 'instance' is initialized to null
            -> When getInstance() is called for the first time, it checks whether 'instance' is null
            -> Since the method is synchronized, only one thread can enter the method at a time
            -> If 'instance' is null, a new singleton object is created and assigned to 'instance'
            -> Subsequent calls return the already created instance

        -> Advantages:
            -> Thread-safe
            -> Prevents creation of multiple singleton objects

        -> Disadvantages:
            -> Entire getInstance() method is synchronized
            -> Every call requires locking and unlocking
            -> Can reduce performance after the object is already created


        -> To improve performance, Double Checked Locking (DCL) can be used.

        -> Double Checked Locking reduces synchronization overhead by synchronizing only the object creation code.

        -> Example: Refer DoubleCheckedLockingSingleton.java

            -> The singleton object is created only when getInstance() is called for the first time.

            -> The first check (if instance == null) is performed without synchronization for better performance.

            -> If instance is null, the thread enters the synchronized block.

            -> Inside the synchronized block, a second null check is performed.

            -> The object is created only once.

            -> The instance variable should be declared as volatile to avoid partially initialized objects due to instruction reordering.

    -> Bill Pugh Singleton Class:
        
        -> This approach uses a static inner helper class to hold the singleton instance.

        -> The singleton instance is created when the inner class is loaded, which happens only when getInstance() is called for the first time.

        -> This approach is thread-safe without requiring synchronization.

        -> Example: Refer BillPughSingleton.java

            -> The BillPughSingleton class contains a private static inner class called SingletonHelper.

            -> The SingletonHelper class has a static variable 'instance' that holds the singleton object.

            -> When getInstance() is called, it returns SingletonHelper.instance.

            -> The SingletonHelper class is not loaded until getInstance() is called, ensuring lazy initialization.

    -> Enum Singleton Class:
        
        -> This approach uses an enum to implement the singleton pattern.

        -> Enums in Java are inherently serializable and provide a guarantee against multiple instantiation, even in the face of complex serialization or reflection attacks.

        -> Example: Refer EnumSingleton.java

            -> The EnumSingleton class is defined as an enum with a single instance called INSTANCE.

            -> The getInstance() method returns the INSTANCE.

            -> This approach is simple and provides built-in thread safety and serialization guarantees.

        -> Advantages:
            -> Simple to implement
            -> Provides built-in thread safety
            -> Provides built-in serialization guarantees
            -> safe against reflection attacks
        -> Disadvantages:
            -> May not be suitable if the singleton class needs to extend another class (since enums cannot extend other classes)

    ->  Singleton With Function and Libraries

        -> This approach uses a functional interface and a library like Java's Supplier to create a singleton instance.

        -> The singleton instance is created lazily when the supplier is called for the first time.

        -> Example 1: Refer SingletonWithFunction.java

            -> The SingletonWithFunction class contains a private static final variable 'instance' of type SingletonWithFunction.

            -> The singleton object is created eagerly when the class is loaded by the JVM.

            -> The constructor is private to prevent object creation from outside the class.

            -> The getInstance() method returns the already created singleton object.

            -> The class also contains additional methods (functions) that can be accessed using the singleton instance.

            -> Example:
                -> SingletonWithFunction obj = SingletonWithFunction.getInstance();
                -> obj.showMessage();

            -> This approach is simple, thread-safe, and suitable when the singleton object is always required.


        -> Example 2: Singleton Usage in Libraries (Logger Example)

            -> Many Java libraries internally use the Singleton design pattern.

            -> Logger is a common real-world example of Singleton usage.

            -> Example:
                -> private static final Logger logger =
                        Logger.getLogger(Main.class.getName());

            -> The Logger object is shared and reused instead of creating a new logger object every time.

            -> This improves performance and ensures centralized logging across the application.

            -> Example Usage:
                -> logger.info("Application Started");

            -> Real-world libraries/frameworks using Singleton concepts:
                -> Logger
                -> Runtime class
                -> Spring Singleton Beans
                -> Database Connection Pool Managers

=> Singleton With Framework: Spring, Guice

    -> Spring Framework provides built-in support for Singleton beans.

    -> By default, Spring beans are singleton scoped, meaning that only one instance of the bean is created and shared across the entire application context.

    -> Example:
        -> @Component
           public class MySingletonService {
               // Service methods
           }

    -> Guice from Google is also a framework to prepare singleton objects and an alternative to Spring.